<h2 id="s1">1. Executive Summary</h2>
<p>Trip Expense Tracker is a Progressive Web App designed for vacation travel expense tracking. Built as a companion to the Daily Expense Tracker, it takes a fundamentally different approach — instead of structured forms with buttons and dropdowns, it provides a <strong>freeform notepad</strong> where users type expenses exactly as they would in Apple Notes.</p>
<p>The app parses natural-language entries like <code>food 250</code>, <code>mrt 40</code>, <code>hotel deposit 1200 cc</code> and automatically extracts the item name, amount, payment method, and expense type. A summary tab provides real-time breakdowns by day, cash vs card, with currency-aware formatting.</p>

<div class="highlight">
<strong>Key achievement:</strong> Entering a vacation expense takes exactly one action — type a line like <code>lunch 350</code> and press Enter. No taps, no selections, no currency symbols needed. The parser handles everything.
</div>

<p>Data syncs to Google Sheets via Apps Script using a smart diff strategy — only new or changed rows are written, never delete-and-rewrite. This enables real-time sync while keeping the sheet clean for downstream analysis.</p>

<!-- ═══ SECTION 2 ═══ -->
<h2 id="s2">2. Design Philosophy & Goals</h2>

<h3>2.1 Core Principle: Vacation Mode</h3>
<p>The app is designed for use while travelling — on beaches, in transit, at restaurants. Every design decision optimizes for <strong>minimum friction</strong>. The user should spend less time on the app than it takes to unlock their phone.</p>

<table>
<tr><th>Goal</th><th>Approach</th></tr>
<tr><td>Speed of entry</td><td>Freeform notepad — type naturally, no forms or buttons</td></tr>
<tr><td>Zero learning curve</td><td>Same format as Apple Notes — if you can type "food 250", you can use the app</td></tr>
<tr><td>Multi-currency</td><td>Per-trip currency selection with locale-aware formatting</td></tr>
<tr><td>Offline capable</td><td>PWA with service worker; entries save to localStorage, sync later</td></tr>
<tr><td>Visual summary</td><td>Auto-parsed summary with cash/card breakdown, daily totals</td></tr>
<tr><td>Data persistence</td><td>Google Sheets backend for backup and cross-device access</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>2.2 Notepad-First vs Form-First</h3>
<p>The Daily Expense Tracker uses a form-first approach: structured buttons for category, subcategory, payment mode. This works for daily tracking where precision matters and categories are well-defined.</p>
<p>The Trip Expense Tracker inverts this: <strong>intelligence lives in the parser, not the interface</strong>. The user writes freely; the app figures out what they meant. This is better for travel because:</p>
<ul>
<li>Expense names are unpredictable (restaurant names, local transport types)</li>
<li>Speed matters more than categorization</li>
<li>Users don't want to navigate UI while sightseeing</li>
<li>A simple text area works one-handed on a moving bus</li>
</ul>

<h3>2.3 UI Language</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Glassmorphism:</strong> Translucent panels on soft grey surface, matching Daily Expense Tracker</li>
<li><strong>Indigo accent:</strong> #4f46e5 for headers, #6366f1 for buttons and active tabs</li>
<li><strong>Thin borders:</strong> 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.08) throughout</li>
<li><strong>No shadows, no gradients</strong> in the content area — frosted glass effect handles depth</li>
</ul>

