<h2 id="s5">5. Parsing Engine — 6 Stage Pipeline</h2>
<p>The parser is the core intelligence of the app. Every line of notepad text passes through 6 stages in sequence:</p>

<h3>Stage 1 — Line Classification</h3>
<p>Each line is classified as either a <strong>date header</strong> or an <strong>expense entry</strong>. Date detection uses regex matching for multiple formats:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Format</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
<tr><td>Day + Month</td><td><code>28 Feb</code>, <code>1 Mar</code>, <code>15 January</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Compact</td><td><code>2mar</code>, <code>28feb</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>With separators</td><td><code>02-Mar</code>, <code>1/mar</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>Month first</td><td><code>Mar 1</code>, <code>Feb 28</code></td></tr>
</table>
<p>Date lines become section headers in the summary. Non-date, non-empty lines proceed to Stage 2.</p>

<h3>Stage 2 — Keyword Extraction</h3>
<p>Three keyword types are detected and flagged:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Keyword</th><th>Detection Pattern</th><th>Action</th><th>Stripped from line?</th></tr>
<tr><td><code>cc</code></td><td><code>/\bcc\b/i</code></td><td>Sets method = "cc"</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>atm</code> / <code>withdrawal</code></td><td><code>/\batm\b/i</code> or <code>/\bwithdr[a]?w[a]?l?\b/i</code></td><td>Sets type = "withdrawal"</td><td>Yes</td></tr>
<tr><td><code>deposit</code></td><td><code>/\bdeposit\b/i</code></td><td>Sets type = "deposit"</td><td><strong>No</strong> — kept in item name</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="highlight">
<strong>Design decision:</strong> "deposit" stays in the item name for clarity (<code>hotel deposit 1200</code> → "Hotel Deposit"), while "atm" and "withdrawal" are stripped because the tag conveys the same information.
</div>

<h3>Stage 3 — Comma Stripping</h3>
<p>Commas are removed from numbers to support both Indian and Western notation:</p>
<pre><code>// Applied twice to catch nested patterns
line = line.replace(/(\d),(\d)/g, "$1$2").replace(/(\d),(\d)/g, "$1$2");
// "10,00,000" → "1000000"
// "1,000,000" → "1000000"</code></pre>

<h3>Stage 4 — Math Evaluation</h3>
<p>Mathematical expressions are found and evaluated using a safe evaluator:</p>
<pre><code>function safeMathEval(expr) {
  const clean = expr.replace(/\s/g, "");
  if (!/^[\d+\-*/().]+$/.test(clean)) return null;  // Only allow safe chars
  if (!/[+\-*/()]/.test(clean)) return null;          // Must have an operator
  try {
    const result = new Function("return (" + clean + ")")();
    if (typeof result === "number" && isFinite(result) && result >= 0)
      return Math.round(result * 100) / 100;
    return null;
  } catch { return null; }
}</code></pre>
<p>The regex <code>/[\d]+(?:\.\d+)?[\s]*[+\-*/()][\s\d+\-*/().]*[\d)]/g</code> finds math-like sequences in the line. Supports <code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>/</code>, parentheses, and decimals. Negative results are rejected (travel expenses are positive).</p>

<h3>Stage 5 — Amount Extraction</h3>
<p>If no math expression found, three patterns are tried in order:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Priority</th><th>Pattern</th><th>Example</th><th>Regex</th></tr>
<tr><td>1</td><td>Bare number (after keyword stripping)</td><td><code>atm 5000</code> → 5000</td><td><code>/^(\d+(?:\.\d+)?)\s*$/</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>2</td><td>Number at start</td><td><code>35 metro</code> → 35</td><td><code>/^(\d+(?:\.\d+)?)\s+(.+)/</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>3</td><td>Number at end</td><td><code>7-11 55</code> → 55</td><td><code>/^(.+?)\s+(\d+(?:\.\d+)?)\s*$/</code></td></tr>
</table>
<p>Falls back to 0 if no number found (entry noted without amount).</p>

<h3>Stage 6 — Item Naming</h3>
<p>Whatever text remains after amount extraction becomes the item name. Empty items get default names based on type:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Type</th><th>Default Name</th><th>Example Input</th></tr>
<tr><td>withdrawal</td><td>"ATM withdrawal"</td><td><code>atm 5000</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>deposit</td><td>"Deposit"</td><td><code>deposit 1000</code></td></tr>
<tr><td>expense</td><td>"—"</td><td>(rare, number-only line)</td></tr>
</table>

