<h2 id="s15">15. Design Decisions & Trade-offs</h2>

<h3>15.1 Why Not Multi-Currency Per Trip?</h3>
<p>The original prototype parsed currency from each line (<code>food 25rs</code>, <code>mrt 40 baht</code>). This was abandoned because:</p>
<ul>
<li>Added complexity to every line typed</li>
<li>Most trips use one currency for 90%+ of transactions</li>
<li>Currency conversion rates change daily — in-app conversion would be unreliable</li>
<li>Single currency per trip keeps the summary clean and totals meaningful</li>
</ul>

<h3>15.2 Why Smart Diff Instead of Append-Only?</h3>
<p>The Daily Tracker uses pure append (one POST per submit). The Trip Tracker can't do this because the notepad is re-parsed entirely on every sync. Append-only would create duplicates. Smart diff was chosen over delete-and-rewrite to minimize sheet operations and preserve row stability.</p>

<h3>15.3 Why No Categories?</h3>
<p>Travel expenses don't fit neatly into predefined categories. "BTS 1 cc" could be transport. "7-11 55" could be food or shopping. Forcing categorization slows entry and adds zero value during the trip. If analysis is needed later, the item names in the sheet can be manually categorized.</p>

<h3>15.4 Why localStorage Instead of IndexedDB?</h3>
<p>The data is small (text strings). localStorage is simpler, synchronous, and sufficient. IndexedDB would add complexity with no meaningful benefit for this use case.</p>

<h3>15.5 Why Separate Apps Script Deployments?</h3>
<p>Each Google Sheet has its own Apps Script project. The Daily Tracker's Code.gs lives in the "Form entries" sheet; the Trip Tracker's Code.gs lives in the "Trips" sheet. They can't share a deployment. This is actually beneficial — changes to one can't break the other.</p>

<!-- ═══ SECTION 16 ═══ -->
<h2 id="s16">16. Inputs for Future AI Models</h2>

<div class="highlight">
<strong>Critical context for any AI continuing work on this project:</strong>
</div>

<ol>
<li><strong>The parser is the core.</strong> All intelligence is in <code>parseLine()</code>. Any new feature (new keywords, new math operators, new patterns) must be added there. The UI is intentionally dumb.</li>
<li><strong>"deposit" is NOT stripped</strong> from the line — unlike "atm" and "cc" which are removed. This was a deliberate design choice for readability.</li>
<li><strong>Three formatting functions exist.</strong> <code>fmt()</code> for table amounts (full numbers), <code>fmtC()</code> for daily totals (K/M for big currencies), <code>fmtBox()</code> for stat boxes (compact, no decimals, locale-aware). Don't mix them.</li>
<li><strong>Day tallies exclude ATM and deposits.</strong> Only <code>type === "expense"</code> entries count in daily totals and summary boxes.</li>
<li><strong>Commas are stripped twice</strong> — <code>.replace(/(\d),(\d)/g, "$1$2")</code> applied twice to handle Indian notation where commas nest (10,00,000 → first pass → 100,0000 → second pass → 1000000).</li>
<li><strong>Smart diff is positional.</strong> Entry 1 in notepad matches row 1 for that trip in sheet. Reordering entries in the notepad will cause all rows to be "updated" even if content is the same — just in different positions. This is acceptable for the rare reorder case.</li>
<li><strong>SCRIPT_URL is in app.js line 3.</strong> If empty, sync is disabled but the app works fully offline with localStorage.</li>
<li><strong>Service worker cache must be bumped</strong> on changes — update the version string in <code>CACHE_NAME</code>. Users on cached old versions won't see updates until the worker re-activates.</li>
<li><strong>Two separate sheet tabs.</strong> "Expenses" is the structured data (for charts/analysis). "Notes" is the raw text (for cross-device sync). They must stay in sync — doPost writes to both.</li>
<li><strong>The app is a companion</strong> to Daily Expense Tracker, not a replacement. They share visual language but have completely different data models, backends, and use cases.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Known Limitations</h3>
<ol>
<li>No edit or delete of individual entries (only via notepad re-edit and re-sync)</li>
<li>No currency conversion — single currency per trip</li>
<li>No charts or graphs — stat boxes and table only</li>
<li>No budget tracking or spending alerts</li>
<li>Parser can misinterpret lines with multiple numbers (e.g., "Metro 1 10" → item "Metro 1", amount 10)</li>
<li>Auth token visible in frontend JS (acceptable for personal use)</li>
<li>Full sheet scan on doPost comparison — works fine for typical trip sizes (&lt;100 entries)</li>
<li>No multi-trip summary or trip-to-trip comparison</li>
</ol>

